"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Nehemiah chapters 11–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-nehemiah-11-12.py

Ch 11: The settlement lists for Jerusalem and Judah's towns
  - The lot-casting for Jerusalem's repopulation (1/10) → remnant theology, Acts 1 lot
  - Judah and Benjamin as the post-exilic core → the two tribes of the Southern Kingdom
    through which both the Davidic and Benjaminite strands of Israel's story continue
  - Priestly genealogies → the Aaronic priesthood maintained until Christ's once-for-all
    high-priestly work (Heb 7-9)
  - Land settlement → the temporary restoration pointing toward the eternal inheritance

Ch 12: Priestly registers, high-priestly succession, and the wall dedication
  - High-priestly succession (Jeshua → Eliashib → Joiada → Jaddua) → Heb 7's argument
    about the Aaronic priesthood's limitation and Christ's eternal Melchizedekan priesthood
  - The Book of Chronicles as the divine record → the Book of Life
  - The wall dedication (vv27-43): the two great thanksgiving choirs → eschatological
    double-choir worship in the heavenly Jerusalem; the great joy exceeding all Israel
    can contain → the inexpressible joy of the redeemed (1 Pet 1:8; Rev 19)
  - The singers' daily portions sustained → Christ as the Living Bread sustaining
    those who serve in his name
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>The lot-casting (<em>gôrālôt</em>) that brought one in every ten people to live in Jerusalem reflects the providential-selection theology that recurs at critical moments in Israel&rsquo;s story — the Urim and Thummim for priestly discernment, the lot to identify Achan (Josh 7), the lot for apportioning Canaan (Josh 14-21). In the NT, the apostles cast lots to replace Judas (Acts 1:26), the final OT-form use of providential selection before the Spirit takes that function permanently at Pentecost. The <em>one-in-ten</em> fraction mirrors the tithe — a portion set apart as holy for God&rsquo;s service. The Jerusalem settlers function as a kind of human tithe, consecrated to the holy city. Christ as the one who fully consecrated himself to Jerusalem — entering it to die — fulfills what the lot-cast settlers could only provisionally enact.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The community&rsquo;s praise for those who <strong>willingly offered</strong> (<em>miṯnaddĕḇîm</em>, those who devoted themselves voluntarily) to live in Jerusalem echoes the Deuteronomic theology of freewill offerings and the voluntary warriors of Judg 5:2 (&lsquo;When leaders lead in Israel, when the people willingly offer themselves&rsquo;). Voluntary consecration as a category anticipates the <em>hĕkîn</em> (I prepared a body for you) of Ps 40:6-8 quoted in Heb 10:5-7: the ultimate volunteer is Christ himself, who comes in the body prepared for him and says &lsquo;I have come to do your will.&rsquo;</p>",
    "3": "<p>The general summary of settlement — leaders in Jerusalem, others in their ancestral towns with their land-portion — establishes the covenant-restoration premise: the land has been returned to families according to their tribal-ancestral claims. This provisional restoration anticipates the final inheritance: Peter applies the promise-of-land language to the eternal inheritance &lsquo;imperishable, undefiled, and unfading, kept in heaven for you&rsquo; (1 Pet 1:4). The temple servants (<em>nĕtînîm</em>) appear here alongside priests and Levites — the full spectrum of those consecrated to divine service is being reconstituted.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The settlement of representatives from <strong>Judah and Benjamin</strong> in Jerusalem continues the post-exilic community&rsquo;s identity as the two-tribe remnant that YHWH preserved through the exile. Judah is the tribe through which the Davidic promise flows (Gen 49:10: &lsquo;the scepter shall not depart from Judah&rsquo;); Benjamin gave Israel its first king (Saul) and later Paul, the apostle to the Gentiles (Rom 11:1: &lsquo;I myself am an Israelite, a descendant of Abraham, a member of the tribe of Benjamin&rsquo;). The genealogical listing of Judahite families preserves the lineage register through which the Messiah&rsquo;s descent can be traced.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Judahite lineage chain — Maaseiah son of Baruch, son of Col-hozeh, son of Hazaiah, son of Adaiah, son of Joiarib, son of Zechariah — is a preserved genealogical record of those who maintained Judahite identity through the exile and return. The covenant-community&rsquo;s meticulous genealogical record-keeping reflects the theological conviction that YHWH&rsquo;s promises are borne by specific people in historical succession — the same conviction that drives Matthew&rsquo;s and Luke&rsquo;s genealogies of Christ (Matt 1:1-17; Luke 3:23-38).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The <strong>468 Perez descendants</strong> are men of the senior Judahite clan — Perez, son of Judah by Tamar (Gen 38), whose line eventually produced Boaz, Obed, Jesse, and David (Ruth 4:18-22; Matt 1:3). The mention of &lsquo;capable men&rsquo; (<em>anšê ḥayil</em>, men of valor) links them to the warrior-community tradition. Perez&rsquo;s birth story — a breach (<em>perēṣ</em>) through which the unexpected son bursts out first — is itself a type of the unexpected breaking-forth of God&rsquo;s purposes through the line that becomes David&rsquo;s and then Christ&rsquo;s.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Benjaminite lineage begins with Sallu son of Meshullam and extends through a chain of names. Benjamin, though the smallest tribe (Judg 20:46-48 nearly destroyed it), was the tribe of Saul, the first king, and continued as a remnant-tribe alongside Judah. The Benjaminite presence in Jerusalem reflects the double-tribe continuity that YHWH preserved — both the &lsquo;lion&rsquo; tribe (Judah) and the &lsquo;wolf&rsquo; tribe (Benjamin, Gen 49:27) have their representatives in the holy city.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The <strong>928 Benjaminites</strong> settled in Jerusalem — more than the 468 Judahites. The numerical detail is preserved as historical record and as covenant-accountability data: YHWH knows the count of his people in each tribe. Revelation&rsquo;s sealing of 144,000 &lsquo;from every tribe of the sons of Israel&rsquo; (Rev 7:4-8) reflects the same theological conviction that the covenant community is known in specific, tribal-genealogical detail by God.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The appointment of <strong>Joel son of Zichri</strong> as overseer and <strong>Judah son of Senuah</strong> as second-in-command reflects the civic governance structure of the restored city. The pattern of chief-and-second-in-command appears in royal succession (David and Solomon, Saul and David) and in administrative hierarchies. The prefiguration is slight but present: the two-person governing pair anticipates the apostolic and presbyterian structures of the NT church, where shared leadership and accountability (not sole authority) is the norm.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The priestly listing begins with <strong>Jedaiah son of Joiarib</strong> and Jachin — two of the twenty-four priestly divisions established by David (1 Chr 24:7: Joiarib is the first division; Jedaiah is the second). The preservation of these priestly family names through the exile and into the restoration demonstrates the continuity of the Aaronic priesthood that YHWH had promised would always have a representative before him. Hebrews 7:11-28 argues from this very continuity to demonstrate that the Levitical priesthood was a provisional institution — the fact that perfection was not attained through it (v11) means it was pointing forward to Christ&rsquo;s superior priesthood.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>Seraiah son of Hilkiah</strong>, identified as the chief officer of the house of God, traces a priestly lineage back to the Zadokite line (son of Hilkiah, son of Meshullam, son of Zadok, son of Meraioth, son of Ahitub). The Zadokite priesthood (descended from Zadok, David&rsquo;s high priest who anointed Solomon, 1 Kgs 1:39) was the legitimate Aaronic priestly line preserved through the exilic period. The Ezekielian vision of the restored temple (Ezek 44:15) reserves the inner-court ministry specifically for the Zadokite priests. The preservation of this specific lineage through exile and return maintained the institutional link to the Aaronic covenant until it found its ultimate fulfillment in Christ&rsquo;s eternal priesthood.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The count of <strong>822 serving relatives</strong> from one priestly family and the addition of Adaiah son of Jeroham&rsquo;s clan reflects the large scale of the temple service personnel. These 822 — plus 242 more in v13 and 128 in v14 — are the men whose daily service maintained the sacrificial system that pointed forward to the once-for-all sacrifice of Christ. The regularity and multiplicity of their service (daily, weekly, annual sacrifices) was itself an argument from the OT that no single sacrifice was sufficient — the repetition was a feature pointing toward the need for a better sacrifice (Heb 10:1-4).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The <strong>242 heads of ancestral houses</strong> under Adaiah son of Jeroham constitute the governing layer of the priestly community. The genealogical chain — Jeroham, Pelaliah, Amzi, Zechariah, Pashur, Malchijah — includes Pashur son of Malchijah, a name that appears in Jeremiah&rsquo;s narrative (Jer 38:1) as one of the officials who had Jeremiah thrown into the cistern. That family name is now redeemed in the post-exilic restoration — a minor but characteristic pattern of how YHWH restores and redeems the names of those who served him through difficult times.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The <strong>128 men of valor</strong> under Zabdiel son of Haggedolim complete the priestly count. The description <em>anšê gibbôrîm</em> (men of valor/might) applied to priests is unusual — priests are typically described by their purity qualifications, not their military virtue. The application of the warrior-virtue vocabulary to priests suggests that in the post-exilic community, temple service was understood as a form of spiritual warfare — a theme that Ephesians 6:10-18 develops in its armor-of-God passage, where the full armor is understood as the equipment for spiritual battle.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Levitical listing begins with <strong>Shemaiah son of Hasshub</strong> and continues through several chains. The Levites were the tribe of Moses and Aaron, dedicated to the service of the tabernacle/temple in lieu of land inheritance (Num 18:20-24). Their position as the &lsquo;middle tier&rsquo; between the high priests (Aaron&rsquo;s sons) and the people in the camp formation of the wilderness march (Num 2-3) anticipates the mediatorial function — a type that finds its fulfillment in Christ as the one Mediator between God and humanity (1 Tim 2:5).</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>Shabbethai and Jozabad</strong> were in charge of the external affairs of the house of God — the outside business and logistics of the temple complex, as distinct from the interior ritual service. The division between interior and exterior service reflects the tiered-access architecture of the temple: the holy of holies, the inner courts, the outer courts, the city, and the surrounding territory formed concentric circles of holiness that governed who could go where. The veil that separated the holy of holies from the rest of the temple (Exod 26:31-35) was torn from top to bottom at Christ&rsquo;s death (Matt 27:51), abolishing the interior-exterior distinction and opening full access to the presence of God for all who come through Christ (Heb 10:19-22).</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>Mattaniah son of Micha</strong>, who directed the thanksgiving in prayer (<em>rôš hattĕhillāh</em>, leader of praise/thanksgiving), is one of the most significant Levitical appointments. Mattaniah&rsquo;s lineage through Micha, Zabdi, and Asaph connects to the Asaphite guild — the psalm-writers of David&rsquo;s musical establishment (1 Chr 25:1-2; Asaph psalms: Ps 50, 73-83). The ongoing preservation of Asaphite praise leadership in the post-exilic community maintained the liturgical-poetic tradition that David had instituted. Christ at the Last Supper sang a hymn with his disciples (Matt 26:30; Mark 14:26) — almost certainly the Hallel psalms (Ps 113-118, Asaphite and Davidic material), enacting the praise tradition at the moment it was being fulfilled.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The total of <strong>284 Levites in the holy city</strong> — a small number for the temple service roles — reflects the post-exilic reality that many Levites had not returned from Babylon. Ezra 8:15 records that Ezra found no Levites among the returnees of his second aliyah and had to specifically recruit them. The thinness of the Levitical personnel is a shadow of the full restoration, which the prophets anticipated as including the re-gathering of all the scattered people (Isa 11:11-12; Jer 23:3-4). The eschatological fulfillment is the gathering of worshippers from every nation who serve in the temple of the new creation (Rev 21:24-27).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The <strong>172 gatekeepers</strong> under Akkub and Talmon maintained the threshold ministry of the temple — guarding the gates that separated the holy from the profane, the pure from the impure. The office of gatekeeper is the subject of Psalm 84:10 (&lsquo;I would rather be a doorkeeper in the house of my God than dwell in the tents of the wicked&rsquo;), which captures the theology that proximity to YHWH&rsquo;s presence is more valuable than any other position. Christ declared himself the gate for the sheep (John 10:7-9: &lsquo;I am the gate; whoever enters through me will be saved&rsquo;), claiming the threshold-mediator function that the gatekeepers held institutionally.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The notice that the rest of Israel — including priests and Levites — settled in all the other towns of Judah, &lsquo;each on his own inheritance,&rsquo; establishes the covenant-land distribution as the organizing principle of post-exilic settlement. The <em>naḥălāh</em> (inheritance) of each family is a theological claim: YHWH&rsquo;s land is distributed to his covenant people as a permanent grant, not a purchase or conquest. Peter applies the <em>naḥălāh</em>-language to the eternal inheritance of those in Christ (1 Pet 1:4): the physical land-inheritance of Canaan was a type of the eternal inheritance Christ secures for his people.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The <strong>temple servants (Nethinim)</strong> on the Ophel under Ziha and Gispa were the lowest-status workers in the temple hierarchy — originally dedicated by Joshua (their name is related to the Hiphil of <em>nātan</em>, to give/dedicate) or captives given to the Levites for service (Num 31:47; Ezra 8:20). Their inclusion in the restored community alongside priests and Levites reflects the theme of the gathering of the marginalized into the covenant people — a theme that culminates in Isa 56:3-8 (&lsquo;Let not the foreigner who has joined himself to YHWH say, &ldquo;YHWH will surely separate me from his people.&rdquo;&rsquo;) and in Christ&rsquo;s welcome of the Gentiles as co-heirs (Eph 2:19-22).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The appointment of <strong>Uzzi son of Bani</strong> as overseer of the Levites in Jerusalem, noted to be from the singing family of Asaph, reflects the Davidic pattern in which the Asaphite guild held leadership in Levitical worship organization. The <em>dĕḇar hammelek</em> (word of the king) in v23 that required a fixed daily portion for the singers shows that the Persian king Artaxerxes had formalized the support of temple music — a secular authority protecting sacred worship. NT parallels: governing authorities providing space for the church&rsquo;s worship (Rom 13:1-7; 1 Pet 2:13-17).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The <strong>king&rsquo;s decree</strong> that singers receive a fixed daily portion (<em>piqqudat yôm bĕyômô</em>) is a striking detail: the Persian imperial administration officially funded the liturgical singers of the Jerusalem temple. This echoes Darius&rsquo;s decree in Ezra 6:8-10 that the temple&rsquo;s expenses be paid from the royal treasury. The providential use of pagan imperial power to sustain YHWH&rsquo;s worship is a repeated pattern: Cyrus&rsquo;s decree (Ezra 1), Darius&rsquo;s affirmation (Ezra 6), Artaxerxes&rsquo;s support for Ezra and Nehemiah. The NT parallel is the use of Roman peace (Pax Romana) to enable the rapid spread of the gospel — YHWH using the structures of human empire to advance his purposes.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>Pethahiah son of Meshezabeel</strong>, from the line of Zerah son of Judah, was &lsquo;at the king&rsquo;s side for all matters concerning the people&rsquo; — a royal liaison officer. Zerah was the twin of Perez, born with a scarlet thread on his wrist (Gen 38:28-30) in a birth narrative of unexpected reversal. The preservation of both Perez and Zerah descendants in the post-exilic community maintains both strands of the Judahite line that flowed from Judah&rsquo;s union with Tamar. Matthew includes Tamar in Jesus&rsquo;s genealogy (Matt 1:3), making the irregular Perez-Zerah birth story part of the Messiah&rsquo;s own family line.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The settlement in <strong>Kiriath-arba (Hebron)</strong> and its villages begins a geographic list of restored Judean settlements. Hebron is the city of the patriarchs — Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob were all buried in the cave of Machpelah near Hebron (Gen 23; 50:13). It was also David&rsquo;s first capital (2 Sam 2:1-4). The restoration of Judean families to Hebron represents the re-linking of the post-exilic community to the patriarchal promise-chain; these are the towns where YHWH first made covenant with Abraham.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>Jeshua, Moladah, and Beth-pelet</strong> are towns in the Negev region of southern Judah — the semi-arid borderlands that Joshua had allotted to the tribe of Judah (Josh 15:26-32). Their resettlement reconnects the post-exilic community to the full territorial extent of the original tribal allotment. The resettlement is partial — the full land is not yet inhabited — anticipating the complete ingathering that Ezekiel and Isaiah described for the restoration age.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>Beersheba and its villages</strong> was the southernmost point of the traditional land (&lsquo;from Dan to Beersheba&rsquo; = the whole land of Israel). Beersheba was the site of Abraham&rsquo;s covenant with Abimelech (Gen 21:31), Isaac&rsquo;s altar (Gen 26:23-24), and Jacob&rsquo;s departure for Egypt (Gen 46:1-4). Its resettlement is a covenantal act — the community is re-occupying the southernmost boundary point of the patriarchal promise-land.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>Ziklag</strong> was the Philistine city given to David when he was a fugitive from Saul (1 Sam 27:6), which became David&rsquo;s base of operations. Its resettlement by Judahites in the post-exilic period restores it to the Judean sphere. These town-restoration details are not merely administrative records but covenant-fulfillment markers: YHWH&rsquo;s promise that the exiles would return and resettle included specific towns associated with the patriarchal and Davidic narratives.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>En-rimmon, Zorah, and Jarmuth</strong> are towns in the Shephelah and southern Judah. Zorah was the birthplace of Samson (Judg 13:2) — a judge whose life was a complex type of deliverer-through-sacrifice: stronger than all opponents, yet brought down by his own weakness, yet in his death destroying more enemies than in his life. The resurrection-pattern of Samson&rsquo;s final act (Judg 16:30) is one of the more dramatic OT types of Christ&rsquo;s death as the moment of greatest victory.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>Zanoah, Adullam, Lachish, and Azekah</strong> are towns with deep Davidic and prophetic associations. Adullam is the cave where David gathered his band of &lsquo;distressed, indebted, and discontented&rsquo; men (1 Sam 22:1-2) — the original &lsquo;mighty men&rsquo; who became his elite guard. The cave of Adullam is a quiet type of the church: those gathered to Christ are society&rsquo;s marginal, not its powerful (1 Cor 1:26-29), yet they become the community through which YHWH accomplishes his purposes. The &lsquo;settlement from Beersheba to the Valley of Hinnom&rsquo; defines the southern boundary of the restored community.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The <strong>Benjaminite settlements from Geba through Michmash, Aija, and Bethel</strong> recall the geography of Saul&rsquo;s early battles (1 Sam 13-14: the Michmash campaign) and the site of Jacob&rsquo;s dream and YHWH&rsquo;s renewal of the covenant (Gen 28:10-22; 35:1-15). Bethel (&lsquo;house of God&rsquo;) was the place where Jacob saw the heavenly staircase connecting earth to heaven. Jesus echoed this vision when he told Nathanael, &lsquo;you will see heaven opened and the angels of God ascending and descending on the Son of Man&rsquo; (John 1:51) — claiming to be the Bethel-staircase in person.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>Anathoth</strong> was the hometown of Jeremiah (Jer 1:1) and of Abiathar, Solomon&rsquo;s exiled priest (1 Kgs 2:26). Its post-exilic resettlement recalls the Jeremiah tradition — the prophet who most dramatically lived out the theology of exile and return, dictating his scroll in the darkest days of Jerusalem&rsquo;s fall and buying a field as an act of faith in the restoration (Jer 32:6-15). Anathoth&rsquo;s reoccupation by Benjaminites is a minor fulfillment of the prophetic act Jeremiah performed at YHWH&rsquo;s direction.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>Hazor</strong> was a great Canaanite city-state, twice destroyed and rebuilt by Israel (Josh 11; Judg 4), and whose destruction by Tiglath-Pileser III (732 BCE) was a sign of divine judgment (2 Kgs 15:29). <strong>Ramah</strong> was the hometown of Samuel (1 Sam 7:17), the last judge and the one who anointed both Saul and David — the pivotal figure of transition from judges to monarchy. These towns being reoccupied by Benjaminites reconnects the post-exilic community to both the conquest-era and the monarchical-era of Israel&rsquo;s story.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>Hadid, Zeboim, and Neballat</strong> are towns in the western foothills of Judah near the coastal plain. Their inclusion in the Benjaminite settlement list reflects the expansion of the restored community toward the coastal lowlands — the western edge of the land promise. The gradual repopulation of the whole territory is the covenant-fulfillment unfolding in historical installments, with the complete fulfillment still ahead.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>Lod, Ono, and the Valley of Craftsmen (Ge Harashim)</strong> are coastal-plain towns. Lod (later Lydda) is notable in Acts 9:32-35 as the town where Peter healed Aeneas — the NT book of Acts records a Christian community there. The post-exilic Benjaminite settlement of Lod and the subsequent NT activity there is an inadvertent continuity between Nehemiah&rsquo;s restoration and the apostolic expansion. The Valley of Craftsmen was apparently a center of skilled trades — the artisan tradition of the restored community anticipates the NT motif of the church as God&rsquo;s crafted work (<em>poiēma</em>, workmanship; Eph 2:10).</p>",
    "36": "<p>The assignment of some Levitical divisions from Judah to Benjamin reflects the cross-tribal nature of the Levites, who had no tribal territory of their own but were distributed throughout all the tribes (Num 35:1-8). The Levitical presence in both Judah and Benjamin ensured covenant teaching in both tribal territories. The NT church has a similar distributional pattern: the elders/pastors (the NT equivalent of the Levites as covenant-teachers) are distributed throughout every congregation rather than concentrated in one place, ensuring the covenant community is spiritually served wherever it gathers.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The list of priests who came up with Zerubbabel and Jeshua in the first return (538 BCE) includes <strong>Seraiah, Jeremiah, Ezra</strong>, and others. Ezra is mentioned here as a priestly family name carried in the first return (before Ezra the scribe, who represents this family in the second return, c.458 BCE). The continuity of priestly family names across the two returns — Zerubbabel&rsquo;s (Ezra 2) and Ezra&rsquo;s (Ezra 8) — demonstrates the careful genealogical maintenance that preserved the Aaronic priesthood across the exile. Without this record, the sacrificial system&rsquo;s institutional continuity could not be verified. Christ&rsquo;s priestly credentials come from a different source — not genealogy but divine oath (Heb 7:20-22): &lsquo;The Lord has sworn and will not change his mind: &ldquo;You are a priest forever.&rdquo;&rsquo;</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>Amariah, Malluch, Hattush</strong> — three names in the returning priestly families. Hattush appears in Ezra 8:2 as a descendant of David who returned with Ezra&rsquo;s caravan — a name that bridges priestly and royal lines. The interweaving of Davidic and priestly genealogies in the post-exilic lists creates a latent tension that Zechariah&rsquo;s vision resolves: two anointed ones, the priestly Joshua and the royal Zerubbabel (Zech 4:14), eventually merging into the one figure who is both priest and king (Zech 6:12-13: &lsquo;he shall be a priest on his throne&rsquo;) — the typological template for Christ&rsquo;s dual office.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>Shechaniah, Rehum, Meremoth</strong> — priestly family names preserved across the exile. Meremoth son of Uriah the priest weighs the silver and gold vessels when Ezra&rsquo;s caravan arrives (Ezra 8:33) and rebuilds two sections of the wall (Neh 3:4,21). The multi-context presence of these names across Ezra-Nehemiah shows the same priestly families involved in every aspect of the restoration — teaching, building, weighing, serving. Their comprehensive engagement with the whole restoration project is a type of the NT priests (1 Pet 2:9: &lsquo;a royal priesthood&rsquo;) called to offer spiritual sacrifices across every domain of life.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>Iddo, Ginnetho, Abijah</strong> — Abijah gives his name to the eighth priestly division (1 Chr 24:10), the division to which Zechariah, father of John the Baptist, belonged (Luke 1:5: &lsquo;a priest named Zechariah, who belonged to the priestly division of Abijah&rsquo;). The genealogical link is striking: Abijah&rsquo;s priestly family, returning with Zerubbabel in 538 BCE, maintains its priestly identity through Nehemiah&rsquo;s time and into the NT period — and it is from this family that John the Baptist is born. The forerunner of Christ emerges from one of the priestly families listed here.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>Miamin, Maadiah, Bilgah</strong> — priestly family names carried forward. Bilgah is the fifteenth priestly division (1 Chr 24:14). The regular preservation of all twenty-four priestly divisions through the exile and restoration maintained the entire institutional cycle of temple service. The NT church&rsquo;s equivalent — the full range of gifts distributed throughout the body (1 Cor 12:4-11) — ensures that no part of the ministry of Christ&rsquo;s body is absent from any era of the church&rsquo;s life.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>Shemaiah, Joiarib, Jedaiah</strong> conclude the first set of returning priestly families. Joiarib is the first of the twenty-four priestly divisions (1 Chr 24:7); Jedaiah is the second. The Maccabean dynasty would emerge from the Joiarib priestly family (1 Macc 2:1: Mattathias was of the Joiarib division), making this otherwise unremarkable list-entry the genealogical root of the Hasmonean dynasty — the priestly rulers who governed Judea in the period between Nehemiah and the birth of Christ.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The summary that these were &lsquo;the leading priests and their associates in the days of Jeshua&rsquo; links the priestly register to the first high priest of the restoration — Jeshua (Joshua) son of Jozadak, the high priest who returned with Zerubbabel and presided over the altar and foundation-laying of the Second Temple (Ezra 3:2,8). Joshua/Jeshua is a name form of the same root as the Greek <em>Iēsous</em> (Jesus). The high priest Jeshua presiding over the Second Temple&rsquo;s establishment is a powerful type of Jesus Christ presiding over the living temple of his body (John 2:19-21; Eph 2:21-22).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Levites who returned — Jeshua, Binnui, Kadmiel, Sherebiah, Judah, and Mattaniah — led the songs of thanksgiving. The <em>hôdôt</em> (thanksgiving songs/hymns) were Levitical compositions performed at designated moments in the temple liturgy. Mattaniah&rsquo;s role in directing thanksgiving connects to his grandson (v17 of ch11) who holds the same role in Nehemiah&rsquo;s time — the Asaphite thanksgiving tradition is a multi-generational inheritance. The eschatological endpoint of this tradition is the great thanksgiving chorus of Rev 7:9-12, where the vast multitude from every nation stands before the throne singing, &lsquo;Salvation belongs to our God who sits on the throne, and to the Lamb.&rsquo;</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>Bakbukiah and Unni</strong> and their associates stood opposite their fellow Levites during the service watches — the antiphonal worship structure of the temple. The two-choir arrangement, with one choir responding to another, reflects the binary praise pattern established by David (1 Chr 25:6-7) and later echoed in the heavenly worship of Revelation 4-5, where the four living creatures and the twenty-four elders respond in alternating praise. The wall dedication ceremony of vv27-43 enacts exactly this two-choir arrangement — the structure of heaven&rsquo;s worship replicated in Jerusalem&rsquo;s liturgy.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The high-priestly genealogy: <strong>Jeshua fathered Joiakim, Joiakim fathered Eliashib, and Eliashib fathered Joiada</strong>. This three-generation chain spans the period from the first return (Jeshua) through Nehemiah&rsquo;s governorship (Eliashib, his contemporary) and beyond. Hebrews 7:23 contrasts the Levitical priests — &lsquo;the former priests were many in number, because they were prevented by death from continuing in office&rsquo; — with Christ, who &lsquo;holds his priesthood permanently because he continues forever.&rsquo; The succession chain itself, generation after generation, is the evidence Hebrews cites for the inadequacy of the Aaronic system: it cannot produce a priest who lives forever.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The chain continues: <strong>Joiada fathered Jonathan, and Jonathan fathered Jaddua</strong>. Jaddua was the high priest at the time of Alexander the Great&rsquo;s conquest (332 BCE) — Josephus records a famous meeting between Jaddua and Alexander (Antiquities 11.8.3-7) in which Alexander bowed before the high priest after recognizing him from a dream. Whether historically accurate or legendary, the story reflects the Macedonian world&rsquo;s encounter with the Jerusalem priesthood. After Jaddua, the high-priestly succession continues into the Seleucid period and eventually the corruption of the office under Jason and Menelaus (2 Macc 4), preparing the context for the Maccabean revolt and the eventual Herodian-Roman period in which Christ arrives.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The list of priestly family heads &lsquo;<strong>in the days of Joiakim</strong>&rsquo; — Meraiah from Seraiah&rsquo;s line, Hananiah from Jeremiah&rsquo;s line, and others — reflects the second generation of the priestly restoration. Each generation maintained its family identity within the twenty-four-division structure. The transition from Joiakim&rsquo;s generation to Eliashib&rsquo;s and then to Joiada&rsquo;s corresponds to the period from early Second Temple establishment (c.515 BCE) through Nehemiah (c.445 BCE) — the priestly structure functions as the backbone of institutional continuity during a period of significant Persian-period change.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>Ezra&rsquo;s line: Meshullam; Amariah&rsquo;s line: Jehohanan</strong> — The Ezra priestly family had its representative in Meshullam in Joiakim&rsquo;s time; Ezra the scribe himself came later. The preservation of the Ezra family name in the priestly register across generations shows that the scribe-reformer Ezra was not an isolated individual but the most prominent representative of a multi-generational priestly family committed to Torah-observance and community reform. Christ&rsquo;s coming to &lsquo;fulfill the Law and the Prophets&rsquo; (Matt 5:17) follows in the tradition of priestly interpreters like Ezra who devoted themselves to the full implementation of the Torah.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>Malluch&rsquo;s line: Jonathan; Shebaniah&rsquo;s line: Joseph</strong> — each priestly division maintaining its family head across generations. The institution of the covenant people requires this kind of unglamorous generational continuity — families preserving names, roles, and obligations across decades and centuries. Hebrews 3:1-6 contrasts Moses (a servant in God&rsquo;s house) with Christ (the Son over God&rsquo;s house), and the house itself is the covenant community whose continuity from generation to generation is sustained by Christ himself.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>Harim&rsquo;s line: Adna; Meraioth&rsquo;s line: Helkai</strong>. Harim is the third priestly division (1 Chr 24:8); in Ezra 10:21, members of the Harim priestly family were among those who had taken foreign wives — evidence that the same family names appear in both failure and restoration. The gospel is precisely the story of how families and individuals caught in covenant failure are restored to covenant service — the Harim family among the offenders in Ezra 10 and the Harim family holding their priestly post in Nehemiah 12 represents the mercy of covenantal restoration.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>Iddo&rsquo;s line: Zechariah</strong> — Zechariah son of Iddo was the post-exilic prophet (Zech 1:1,7; Ezra 5:1; 6:14) who received the visions of the flying scroll, the four chariots, the high priest Joshua in clean garments, and the BRANCH who would be priest on his throne (Zech 3:8; 6:12-13). The priestly family of Iddo thus produced the prophet who most clearly articulated the coming Messiah as the merger of royal and priestly offices. The Zechariah who is listed as Iddo&rsquo;s priestly representative in Joiakim&rsquo;s time may be the father of the prophet Zechariah or an earlier family member — the family connection to prophetic vision is striking in either case.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>Abijah&rsquo;s line: Zichri; Miniamin&rsquo;s and Moadiah&rsquo;s lines: Piltai</strong>. As noted at v4, the Abijah priestly division is the one from which Zechariah, father of John the Baptist, will come (Luke 1:5). The continuity from Abijah&rsquo;s return with Zerubbabel (v4) through the representative in Joiakim&rsquo;s time (Zichri) to the NT Zechariah in Herod&rsquo;s time — a span of roughly 500 years — is the genealogical chain through which the forerunner of Christ emerges from the priesthood of Israel.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>Bilgah&rsquo;s line: Shammua; Shemaiah&rsquo;s line: Jehonathan</strong>. These mid-list priestly family heads carry forward the institutional maintenance that enabled the Second Temple period&rsquo;s survival as a worshipping community. The preservation of all twenty-four divisions across the exile and through the Second Temple period demonstrates that YHWH&rsquo;s promise to maintain the priesthood (Jer 33:17-22: &lsquo;David shall never lack a man to sit on the throne of the house of Israel, and the Levitical priests shall never lack a man in my presence to offer burnt offerings&rsquo;) was kept in specific, nameable families.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>Joiarib&rsquo;s line: Mattenai; Jedaiah&rsquo;s line: Uzzi</strong>. Joiarib (first priestly division) and Jedaiah (second division) are the leading priestly families whose representatives are named here. The Joiarib family will produce the Maccabees; the Jedaiah family appears in Zechariah&rsquo;s vision (Zech 6:10-15: Heldai, Tobijah, and Jedaiah bring silver and gold from the returned exiles to make a crown for Joshua the high priest — a dramatic acted prophecy of the BRANCH who will be priest on his throne).</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>Sallai&rsquo;s line: Kallai; Amok&rsquo;s line: Eber</strong>. These two priestly families are less prominent in the biblical narrative but their preservation in the list reflects the completeness of the covenant restoration: all twenty-four divisions are accounted for, not just the famous ones. The full-number completion of the priestly roster echoes the language of Revelation 7&rsquo;s sealing of 144,000 (12 × 12 × 1000), where the complete, symbolic totality of the covenant people is gathered.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>Hilkiah&rsquo;s line: Hashabiah; Jedaiah&rsquo;s line: Nethanel</strong>. Hilkiah was the high priest who discovered the scroll of the Torah during Josiah&rsquo;s temple repair (2 Kgs 22:8-10), triggering the great Josianic reform — arguably the most significant Torah-rediscovery event in pre-exilic Israel. The Hilkiah family carrying that legacy forward into the Second Temple period as a continuing priestly line maintains the connection between the Torah-discovery that sparked Josiah&rsquo;s reform and the Torah-centered community of Ezra-Nehemiah.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The registration of Levitical family heads &lsquo;in the days of Eliashib, Joiada, Johanan, and Jaddua&rsquo; — spanning approximately 445-332 BCE — and the notation that the priests were recorded in the Book of Chronicles <em>melaḵût Dāryāweš hapPārsî</em> (in the reign of Darius the Persian) demonstrates the use of Persian imperial dating for the covenant community&rsquo;s own internal records. The interweaving of Persian and covenant history in the administrative records of post-exilic Judah reflects the &lsquo;exile within empire&rsquo; reality that Paul articulates theologically: the covenant people live as citizens of an earthly empire while their true citizenship is in heaven (Phil 3:20).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The <strong>Book of the Chronicles</strong> (<em>sēper diḇrê hayyāmîm</em>) serves as the authoritative record of the Levitical family heads &lsquo;until the days of Johanan son of Eliashib.&rsquo; This genealogical record-keeping — maintaining the covenant community&rsquo;s institutional memory across generations — is a type of the Book of Life in which the names of YHWH&rsquo;s people are inscribed (Exod 32:32-33; Ps 69:28; Dan 12:1; Rev 20:12-15). The difference: the earthly book records genealogical succession; the heavenly book records those whose names are written by grace, not by birth.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The leading Levites — <strong>Hashabiah, Sherebiah, and Jeshua son of Kadmiel</strong> with their associates — standing opposite each other in antiphonal praise is the worship architecture of the Second Temple. This responsive-worship format (one group facing another) structures the liturgy as divine dialogue: the congregation&rsquo;s praise addresses YHWH, and the responsive choir represents YHWH&rsquo;s people receiving back what they give. The heavenly throne room of Revelation (4:8-11; 5:9-14) maintains this dialogical structure — the creatures and elders responding to one another and to the Lamb in layered praise.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>Mattaniah, Bakbukiah, Obadiah, Meshullam, Talmon, and Akkub</strong> as gatekeepers keeping watch at the storerooms represent the full integration of the gate-ministry with the storage-distribution ministry. These are the same Levitical families who appear throughout Ezra-Nehemiah in various service roles. The combined gatekeeper-storeroom role ensured that both access (who enters the holy space) and resource (what is kept in the sacred storerooms) were under Levitical supervision. Christ combines both functions: as the gate (John 10:7-9), he controls access; as the bread from heaven (John 6:35), he is the resource distributed to those who come through the gate.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The summary that these gatekeepers served &lsquo;in the days of Joiakim son of Jeshua son of Jozadak, and in the days of Nehemiah the governor and Ezra the priest-scribe&rsquo; marks the institutional convergence point: the high priestly administration, the civil governor, and the scribal-teaching authority all functioning simultaneously in the restoration community. This three-fold leadership (priestly, royal/governmental, and prophetic-scribal) corresponds to the three offices of Christ — prophet, priest, and king — which in Christ are unified in one person for the first time in Israel&rsquo;s history without the tension and competition that marked the post-exilic three-leader structure.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The <strong>dedication of the wall</strong> (<em>ḥănukkat ḥômat yĕrûšālayim</em>) required gathering all the Levites from their towns for celebration with songs, cymbals, harps, and lyres. The word <em>ḥănukkāh</em> (dedication) is the same word used for the dedication of Solomon&rsquo;s temple (2 Chr 7:9), the dedication of the Second Temple after Zerubbabel&rsquo;s rebuilding (Ezra 6:16-17), and later for the Maccabean rededication of the temple (1 Macc 4:54-59) — the event that gives the Hanukkah festival its name. Each dedication is a covenant-recommitment ceremony. The wall&rsquo;s dedication marks the completed restoration of Jerusalem&rsquo;s protective boundary — a type of the New Jerusalem whose wall is described in Rev 21:12-21.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The singers gathered from the surrounding area, including the <strong>Netophathite villages</strong> near Bethlehem, to participate in the wall dedication. Netophah appears in the genealogies of David&rsquo;s mighty men (2 Sam 23:28-29) as the hometown of several Davidic warriors; in the post-exilic period it became a singers&rsquo; village. The gathering of musicians from the villages around Jerusalem for the dedication echoes David&rsquo;s gathering of musicians for the ark&rsquo;s procession to Jerusalem (2 Sam 6:5: &lsquo;David and all the house of Israel were celebrating before YHWH with all kinds of musical instruments&rsquo;). The wall dedication consciously reenacts the Davidic liturgical tradition.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The singers had established their own villages around Jerusalem — <strong>from Beth-gilgal and from the fields of Geba and Azmaveth</strong>. The existence of dedicated singer-villages reflects the full institutionalization of Davidic worship: not merely individual musicians but entire communities organized around the vocation of temple praise. This anticipates the eschatological community of Revelation in which the 144,000 learn a new song that only they can sing (Rev 14:3) — a community defined by its distinctive worship.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The purification of priests, Levites, people, gates, and wall before the dedication ceremony is the preparatory rite that sanctifies everything associated with the dedication. The cascade of purification — from clergy (priests and Levites) to laity (people) to infrastructure (gates and wall) — reflects the concentric holiness model of the Mosaic cult: sanctity radiates outward from the priests through the community and into the physical spaces they inhabit. The NT equivalent is the purification wrought by Christ&rsquo;s blood: &lsquo;the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin&rsquo; (1 John 1:7), sanctifying the whole people and, by extension, the creation they inhabit (Rom 8:19-21).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Nehemiah organized <strong>two large thanksgiving choirs</strong> (<em>šetê tôdôt</em> gĕdōlôt, two great thanksgiving-choruses) that would walk in opposite directions on top of the wall. The two-choir procession walking in opposite directions around the city walls — meeting at the temple — is one of the most dramatic liturgical acts in the OT. The symmetrical, convergent movement of praise toward the house of God images the gathering of the covenant community from all directions toward the presence of YHWH. Revelation 21:24-26 describes the kings of the earth bringing their glory into the New Jerusalem from all directions — the same convergent-toward-center theology enacted in visual liturgy by Nehemiah&rsquo;s two choirs.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>Hoshaiah followed with half of the leaders of Judah</strong> in one of the two choirs. The leaders of Judah walking on top of the wall — the same wall that was the focal point of their enemies&rsquo; mockery and opposition (Neh 4:1-3) — is a visible act of covenant triumph. What the opponents tried to prevent has been accomplished; the leaders are not merely inside the city but elevated on its completed wall in public procession. The spatial triumph embedded in this scene resonates with the eschatological language of the saints reigning with Christ (Rev 20:4-6) and the city with open gates (Rev 21:25).</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>Azariah, Ezra, and Meshullam</strong> — Ezra is present in the wall-dedication procession, marking his continued central role in the post-exilic restoration. Ezra and Nehemiah, though associated with overlapping periods and complementary reforms, appear together at this climactic moment of communal celebration. The scribe-priest who had led the Torah-reading revival of ch8 and the governor who built the wall both take their places in the thanksgiving procession — the word-ministry and the work-ministry converging in the same act of praise.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>Judah, Benjamin, Shemaiah, and Jeremiah</strong> — the two tribal names (Judah and Benjamin) appear among the participants alongside personal names, blurring the line between tribal identity and individual participation. The covenant community in its procession embodies its double identity: specific individuals with specific names and the collective tribal inheritance of the covenant people. The NT parallel is the church as both individual persons (named and known to God: John 10:3 — &lsquo;he calls his own sheep by name&rsquo;) and collective body (1 Cor 12:27: &lsquo;you are the body of Christ, and each one of you is a part of it&rsquo;).</p>",
    "35": "<p>The <strong>priests with trumpets</strong> — Zechariah son of Jonathan, son of Shemaiah, son of Mattaniah, son of Micaiah, son of Zaccur, son of Asaph — traced through six generations to the Asaphite guild provides the trumpet ministry with deep Davidic roots. Priestly trumpets at sacred occasions were prescribed in Numbers 10:1-10: silver trumpets for assembling the community, breaking camp, going to war, and celebrating festivals. The eschatological use of trumpets in Matthew 24:31 (the great trumpet gathering the elect from the four winds), 1 Cor 15:52 (the last trumpet at the resurrection), and Revelation 8-11 (the seven trumpet judgments) draws on this exact priestly-trumpet tradition.</p>",
    "36": "<p><strong>The instruments of David</strong> (<em>bĕkĕlê šîr dāwîd</em>) are specifically named as the musical equipment for the dedication ceremony — harps, lyres, and the full Davidic ensemble. The reference to &lsquo;the man of God David&rsquo; (v36 in many versions) invokes David&rsquo;s authority as the originator of the musical order for YHWH&rsquo;s worship. Ezra the scribe leads this half of the procession — the scribal-Torah authority walking with Davidic instruments, the law and the liturgy moving together. Christ fulfills both: &lsquo;the law was given through Moses, grace and truth came through Jesus Christ&rsquo; (John 1:17), and &lsquo;he who sanctifies and those who are sanctified are all of one source&rsquo; (Heb 2:11).</p>",
    "37": "<p>The route of the procession — up the stairs of the <strong>City of David</strong> along the wall&rsquo;s ascent, past the House of David, and to the Water Gate — traces the geography of David&rsquo;s original Jerusalem. Walking the ascent of the City of David on the wall recalls David&rsquo;s entry into Jerusalem (2 Sam 5:7: &lsquo;David captured the stronghold of Zion, that is, the City of David&rsquo;) and the ascents of the pilgrimage psalms (Ps 120-134, the Songs of Ascents). The whole procession is a liturgical ascent — a community climbing toward YHWH&rsquo;s presence. Christ&rsquo;s triumphal entry into Jerusalem (Matt 21:1-11) follows the same geography of ascent from the east, with the crowd singing Ps 118 (<em>Hosanna</em>) — the same liturgical pattern Nehemiah&rsquo;s procession enacted.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The <strong>second thanksgiving choir</strong> went in the opposite direction, with Nehemiah and half the people. The governor and the scribe-priest (Ezra) leading the two separate choirs ensures that the civil and religious authority are both present in the worship procession, neither absent. The two choirs converging toward the temple from opposite directions on the wall — one half going south, the other going north — creates a visual image of the entire city encircled by thanksgiving. The New Jerusalem has no temple distinct from God&rsquo;s presence (Rev 21:22: &lsquo;I did not see a temple in the city, because the Lord God Almighty and the Lamb are its temple&rsquo;) — the distinction between approach-path and destination dissolves.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The detailed gate-by-gate route — <strong>Gate of Ephraim, Old Gate, Fish Gate, Tower of Hananel, Tower of the Hundred, Sheep Gate</strong> — names the specific infrastructure that the community had built together under opposition (Neh 3). Each gate named in the procession is a gate that had been repaired by a specific family or group; the dedication procession walked over the achievement of the whole community. The Fish Gate appears in Zeph 1:10 as a site of judgment; in Nehemiah it is a site of dedication. The Sheep Gate, first rebuilt in Neh 3:1, is echoed in John 10:7-9 where Christ calls himself the sheep gate.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Both thanksgiving choirs took their places in <strong>the house of God</strong> — the procession that began on the wall converged in the temple. The wall and the temple are connected: securing the city (the wall) creates the conditions for unimpeded worship (the temple). The convergence of two choirs in the house of God from opposite directions images the eschatological gathering of all God&rsquo;s people from the four corners of the earth into his presence (Isa 11:11-12; Matt 24:31). Christ&rsquo;s final prayer — &lsquo;that they may all be one, just as you, Father, are in me&rsquo; (John 17:21) — is the theological statement that the convergent-choir liturgy enacted spatially.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The priests <strong>Eliakim, Maaseiah, Miniamin, Michaiah, Elioenai, Zechariah, and Hananiah sounded their trumpets</strong> at the climactic moment of the dedication. Seven priests are named — though perhaps coincidentally, the number echoes the seven trumpets of Joshua&rsquo;s Jericho campaign (Josh 6:4-13), where seven priests blowing seven trumpets for seven days brought down the walls of the enemy city. At Jerusalem&rsquo;s wall dedication, priests with trumpets celebrate a wall going up rather than coming down. The reversal is theologically significant: what was defeated (Jericho) and what was built (Jerusalem) are both marked by priestly trumpets — the covenant people&rsquo;s warfare and their habitation both have the same liturgical signature.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The singers sang loudly under the direction of <strong>Jezrahiah</strong>, and the sound was heard far off. The volume of the celebration — the joy loud enough to be heard at a distance — is the sonic parallel to Ezra 3:13 where the &lsquo;sound was heard far off&rsquo; at the weeping-and-shouting mixed celebration when the temple foundation was laid. But where Ezra 3 mingled weeping with joy (the old men mourning the lesser glory of the Second Temple), Nehemiah 12 is described as pure joy (v43). The prophetic promise fulfilled: &lsquo;the ransomed of YHWH shall return and come to Zion with singing; everlasting joy shall be upon their heads; they shall obtain gladness and joy, and sorrow and sighing shall flee away&rsquo; (Isa 35:10; 51:11).</p>",
    "43": "<p>On that day they <strong>offered great sacrifices and rejoiced, for God had given them great joy</strong>. The <em>šimḥāh gĕdôlāh</em> (great joy) given by God (<em>ki-ʾĕlōhîm śimmeḥām śimḥāh gĕdôlāh</em>) is a divine gift, not merely a human emotion — the joy is YHWH&rsquo;s to give, and he gives it in the completion of the wall and the dedication of the city. The women and children joined the celebration so that the joy of Jerusalem was heard far off. This is one of the most joyful scenes in the OT — a community that had rebuilt under threat, mockery, and opposition now celebrating with a joy loud enough to resound across the countryside. Christ&rsquo;s parable of the returned son ends with exactly this image: the father saying to the older son, &lsquo;we had to celebrate and be glad&rsquo; (Luke 15:32). The joy at the restoration of what was lost is not optional — it is YHWH&rsquo;s own response to the gathering of his people.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The practical follow-through: men appointed to oversee the <strong>storerooms for contributions, firstfruits, and tithes</strong> — the institutional sustainability of the dedication&rsquo;s joy. Every great moment of covenant renewal in Nehemiah is followed by administrative provisions for its continuation: the great assembly of ch10 produced a covenant with specific obligations (10:32-39); the wall dedication produces the appointment of storeroom overseers. Christ&rsquo;s institution of the Lord&rsquo;s Supper follows the same pattern: a moment of profound covenantal meaning embedded in an ongoing, regular practice (&lsquo;do this in remembrance of me&rsquo;, Luke 22:19) that sustains the community&rsquo;s covenantal life between the great moments.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The singers and gatekeepers kept their <strong>appointed duties including the requirements of purification</strong>, as David and Solomon had commanded. The explicit reference to David and Solomon&rsquo;s authority grounds the Second Temple&rsquo;s worship order in the royal-cultic legislation of the monarchical period. The post-exilic community is not inventing new practices but restoring the Davidic order. Christ similarly does not abolish but fulfills (Matt 5:17): the entire worship tradition maintained across the generations finds its intended completion in him.</p>",
    "46": "<p><strong>In the days of David and Asaph</strong>, long ago, there had been directors of the singers — a historical anchor for the current worship order. The phrase &lsquo;long ago&rsquo; (<em>miqqedem</em>) from the perspective of Nehemiah&rsquo;s time is already five centuries deep — David lived c.1000 BCE, and Nehemiah is writing c.445 BCE. The community&rsquo;s worship practices are embedded in half a millennium of covenant history, continuously maintained across the disruptions of divided monarchy, Assyrian conquest, Babylonian exile, and Persian restoration. This depth of tradition is evidence that YHWH had preserved his people and their worship through every catastrophe — the same faithfulness that Paul celebrates: &lsquo;he who began a good work in you will carry it to completion&rsquo; (Phil 1:6).</p>",
    "47": "<p>The final verse: all Israel in the days of Zerubbabel and Nehemiah <strong>provided daily portions for the singers and gatekeepers</strong>, setting aside the holy portions for the Levites, and the Levites setting aside a portion for the Aaronic priests. The whole tithe-chain — Israel to Levites to priests — is described as functioning properly, a counterpoint to the breakdown of vv10-14 and the crisis of Ezra 8. The closing image of the book before ch13&rsquo;s reform sequence is of the covenant-support system working as designed: every tier receiving its portion, every ministry sustained. The NT vision of the church at its best has the same quality: &lsquo;they were selling their possessions and belongings and distributing the proceeds to all, as any had need&rsquo; (Acts 2:45) — the covenant community as the place where no one lacks, because all give and all receive.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'nehemiah')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'nehemiah', existing)
    ch11 = len(CHRIST['11']); ch12 = len(CHRIST['12'])
    print(f'Nehemiah 11-12 mkt-christ written ({ch11+ch12} verses: ch11={ch11}, ch12={ch12}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
